eden","1275–Male":"1275–Overleden","1295–Male":"1295–Overleden","1279–Female":"1279–Overleden","Abt 1295":"circa 1295","1315":"1315","1279":"1279","about 1279":"circa 1279","1275":"1275","1295":"1295","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bedfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England"},"en":{"about 1279–":"about 1279–Deceased","1275–Male":"1275–Deceased","1295–Male":"1295–Deceased","1279–Female":"1279–Deceased","Abt 1295":"about 1295","1315":"1315","1279":"1279","about 1279":"about 1279","1275":"1275","1295":"1295","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"CROSIER","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Crozier  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Crozier","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name for one who carried a cross or a bishop's crook or pastoral staff in ecclesiastical processions, from Middle English <i>crosier</i> (Old French <i>crosier, crocier, crosser</i>). It may also denoted a seller of crosses or, as a topographic name, a dweller by a cross (compare 2 below).","French: topographic name for a dweller by a cross or crossroad, an agent derivative of <i>croix</i> ‘cross’ (from Latin <i>crux</i>), or a habitational name from Le Crozier in Rhône-Alpes, a placename of the same etymology."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"Knight","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: status or occupational name from Middle English <i>knight</i> ‘retainer, attendant’ (Old English <i>cniht</i> ‘boy, youth, lad)’. The specialized feudal sense ‘a high-ranking tenant bound to serve his lord as a mounted soldier’ is not known to have ever given rise to the surname, although it is not out of the question that it may occasionally have been used as a nickname, perhaps for someone who played the part of an armed knight in a local pageant.","Irish: sometimes adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac an Ridire</b> ‘son of the knight’. See also   McKnight  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Knights","meanings":["English (East Anglia): variant of   Knight  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"McKnight","meanings":["Irish: part translation of Gaelic <b>Mac an Ridire</b> ‘son of the horseman (Gaelic <i>ridire</i>)’, formerly Anglicized <i>McRuddery</i>.","Scottish (Dumfriesshire and Galloway) and Irish (Ulster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Neachtain</b>, which is usually Anglicized as   McNaughton  ."]}]},{"name":"JOHN","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":11,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":36,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":49,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Sir Knight JOHN CROSIER was born about 1279, in Bedfordshire, England. She had at least 1 son with Sir Knight John Crosier."},"et":{"about 1279–":"umbes 1279–Surnud","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1279–Female":"1279–Surnud","Abt 1295":"umbes 1295","1315":"1315","1279":"1279","about 1279":"umbes 1279","1275":"1275","1295":"1295","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1279–":"noin 1279–Kuollut","1275–Male":"1275–Kuollut","1295–Male":"1295–Kuollut","1279–Female":"1279–Kuollut","Abt 1295":"noin 1295","1315":"1315","1279":"1279","about 1279":"noin 1279","1275":"1275","1295":"1295","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bedfordshire, Englanti, Y